General accidental release prevention and chemical-specific prevention steps:

MPM Silicones has implemented a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of hazardous chemicals known as Process Safety Management (PSM).  The facility is also subject to the New York State Chemical Bulk Storage (CBS) regulation that focuses on preventing spills and releases from hazardous material storage tanks.  Both programs are an integral part of the safety-related operations at GE Silicones.  PSM helps to ensure that proper safety information is in place, operating procedures are followed, chemical hazards are identified, employees and contractors are properly trained, and critical equipment is properly inspected and maintained.  Some of the many specific features in place at GE Silicones to minimize the potential for a chemical accident include:
* Computerized process control systems on chlorosilane and methyl chloride chemical reaction and purification systems to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions (e.g. pressure, temperature, vessel level, flow rate) are immediately identified and corrected;
* Instrumentation and safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error that could lead to a storage tank overfill;
* Secondary containment dikes around storage tanks and loading stations to contain a spill;
* Hydrogen chloride and methyl chloride gas sensors to detect and warn of a release;
* Extensive safety information about the processes reviewed with employees and contractors;
* Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions and safety shut down instructions;
* Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work practices and proper operation of processes;
* Maintenance and inspection programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability and integrity including equipment testing and inspection;
* A management of change process that requi

res the review of proposed plant modifications in order to identify possible hazards before the change is implemented;
* Safety pre-qualification of all contractors;
* Safety reviews prior to startup of processes; andSafety systems and procedures that control hazards during special operations such as welding.
Five year accident history:The MPM Silicones facility experienced one RMP-related incident in the past five years.  In 2000, between 300 and 400 gallons of trimethylchlorosilane were released as the result of the failure of a transfer hose during an off loading operation.  The released material was contained within the dike.  There were no off site impacts or evacuations, although ten on site personnel were sent for medical evaluation.  In an effort to prevent this type of event in the future, the hose was replaced by a permanent loading arm.  The Emergency Response Program:The Waterford, New York site maintains a written emergency response program designed to protect workers, the public, and the environment in the event of a major accidental release.  As part of this program, we have developed and implemented written programs to train all of our employees in the proper response to an incident.  We have also developed and trained more extensively a smaller number of employees to act as an emergency brigade to provide more expertise in responding to more significant events both on and off site.  We have equipped this brigade with equipment needed to respond to emergencies, both on-site and off-site.  This equipment includes three fire trucks, two ambulances, and two hazmat vehicles.  Our trained fire brigade and medical and chemical response teams work closely with area hospitals, industries and other emergency response organizations in the Capital Region.  

